So after You Don't Know Jack, Jellyvision released You Don't Know Jack Sports, followed by You Don't Know Jack Vol. 2, You Don't Know Jack Movies, You Don't Know Jack TV, You Don't Know Jack Vol. 3, You Don't Know Jack Vol. 4, The Ride, You Don't Know Jack Headrush, You Don't Know Jack Offline, Louder, Faster, Funnier, You Don't Know Jack Fifth Dementia.

23
00:02:02,694 --> 00:02:09,318
You don't know Jack Mach 2. You don't know Jack Abatz, which is the third German edition.

24
00:02:09,679 --> 00:02:16,884
You don't know Jack Volume 6, The Lost Gold, which went off the rails a little bit, I guess,

25
00:02:17,684 --> 00:02:20,426
if I'm being honest. A lot of you don't know Jacks.

26
00:02:21,107 --> 00:02:25,990
And it's not like we didn't try to make some other games. Some even made it to market.

27
00:02:27,191 --> 00:02:31,876
Who Wants to be a Millionaire, the PC CD-ROM game, Jellyvision made that one too.

28
00:02:32,216 --> 00:02:35,680
But it was a struggle to break away from being the you-don't-know Jack company.

29
00:02:36,381 --> 00:02:42,647
And then some new consoles came out, and the CD-ROM market kind of evaporated.

30
00:02:43,427 --> 00:02:50,991
and sounds like the beginning of a behind the music story where we all descend into drugs and bankruptcy

31
00:02:51,751 --> 00:02:55,212
and all of that, but it wasn't as dramatic as that.

32
00:02:55,232 --> 00:02:59,974
Jellyvision did go dormant in 2002 and then around 2008 it was revived as Jellyvision Games.

33
00:03:05,977 --> 00:03:09,358
And after some experimentation and research,

34
00:03:09,419 --> 00:03:12,400
Jellyvision Games released its first game, which was

35
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:13,421
You Don't Know Jack, 2011.

36
00:03:18,052 --> 00:03:19,714
Well, we couldn't quite escape it.

37
00:03:21,176 --> 00:03:23,979
We tried branching out into mobile and social games,

38
00:03:24,560 --> 00:03:26,762
but we struggled to make the freemium model work.

39
00:03:27,303 --> 00:03:31,648
And, you know, not as many people played Lieswater or met Octoputz,

40
00:03:31,948 --> 00:03:35,812
the Wordputz mascot up there, as we would have liked.

41
00:03:36,853 --> 00:03:41,375
The thing is, so-called social games aren't actually all that social.

42
00:03:41,415 --> 00:03:47,258
You play them alone in the bathroom or on the couch, not at a party with friends.

43
00:03:47,318 --> 00:03:48,339
And that was kind of our thing.

44
00:03:48,379 --> 00:03:53,361
We wanted games where you play at a party with friends and there's laughter and you

45
00:03:53,401 --> 00:03:56,763
yuck it up and stuff.

46
00:03:56,783 --> 00:04:00,464
And the whole freemium model was difficult for us.

47
00:04:01,593 --> 00:04:07,619
But then a new device came along and we thought, OK, maybe this will help us break back into people's living rooms.

48
00:04:08,140 --> 00:04:09,922
And that was the Ouya.

49
00:04:10,863 --> 00:04:18,871
For those of you who don't remember, the Ouya was a Android console that was a big hit on Kickstarter.

50
00:04:19,432 --> 00:04:24,615
made several million dollars on there. And we thought, oh, this might be a good opportunity

51
00:04:24,675 --> 00:04:31,178
for us to get a new game out, you know, back into people's living rooms where people could

52
00:04:31,198 --> 00:04:39,023
play on their couches with their friends. And so we released You Don't Know Jack on the OUYA.

53
00:04:40,904 --> 00:04:44,846
So we were kind of scrambling at this point. Money was tight.

54
00:04:48,205 --> 00:04:53,770
you know, we had this game, but we had an issue, like how many people are going to buy

55
00:04:54,351 --> 00:05:02,419
four $50 controllers for a $99 console? You know, so we weren't convinced that many people would

56
00:05:02,459 --> 00:05:06,723
be playing You Don't Know Jack with their friends if they didn't each have their own controller.

57
00:05:06,743 --> 00:05:10,467
So we thought, well, if only there's some way, like some device.

58
00:05:11,187 --> 00:05:15,050
that everyone had in their pockets already that they could use to interact with our games.

59
00:05:15,850 --> 00:05:20,813
And that led us to make a mobile controller app that we called JackPad.

60
00:05:22,917 --> 00:05:28,739
Jackpad was problematic for several reasons. For one, you had to install an app. And that's an

61
00:05:28,799 --> 00:05:33,160
immediate roadblock for many users. Very frustrating. Also, everyone needed to be on

62
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:38,182
the same Wi-Fi network, which is also a pain in the butt. And then there's always that person

63
00:05:38,242 --> 00:05:42,843
with a weird phone. At the time, there was Windows phones. We're not going to make a

64
00:05:42,883 --> 00:05:48,345
Windows phone app. And so it was somewhat limiting in that way, too.

65
00:05:50,906 --> 00:05:51,066
Well,

66
00:05:51,864 --> 00:05:58,228
Much to our chagrin, OUYA didn't pan out as we had hoped and so we tried to regroup and figure it

67
00:05:58,288 --> 00:06:03,752
out, figure out what we could do next. We had spent all this time writing content for games

68
00:06:03,792 --> 00:06:08,095
like Lie Swatter that didn't really take off so we thought well maybe we could use that for

69
00:06:08,155 --> 00:06:14,340
something else. Lie Swatter is a simple trivia game where you get statements like blondes have

70
00:06:14,380 --> 00:06:18,723
more fungus problems or hot pink is the most popular selling duct tape color.

71
00:06:20,568 --> 00:06:25,752
and you need to decide if they're true or false. It's really that simple. And we thought, well,

72
00:06:25,772 --> 00:06:30,895
what about movie theaters? Yeah, there's all that time before movies start and there's a giant

73
00:06:30,935 --> 00:06:36,459
screen and people have their phones out anyway. Plus, movie theaters are this evergreen business

74
00:06:36,500 --> 00:06:43,124
that will always be popular, right? This was in 2013 when Netflix still only had one original series.

75
00:06:45,399 --> 00:06:50,222
So we built a version of Lieswater for the big screen and took it to a midnight

76
00:06:50,262 --> 00:06:53,744
showing of Christmas Vacation at the Music Box Theater in Chicago.

77
00:06:53,764 --> 00:06:58,527
And unlike Jackpad, we just had people go to a website,

78
00:06:58,767 --> 00:07:02,910
Togetherplay.tv, and they'd go there,

79
00:07:03,871 --> 00:07:06,332
sign in and interact with the game.

80
00:07:06,492 --> 00:07:08,754
No apps to install, no controllers.

81
00:07:09,194 --> 00:07:10,575
